The complexation ratio of FDA and Ce4+ can be determined by Job's plot experiment and the B–H curve. The sum concentration of Ce4+ and FDA was maintained at 2 μM and the mole fraction of Ce4+ was changed from 0 to 1 [28]. It can be seen that the maximum fluorescence emission recede at 505 nm was appeared when the molecular fraction of Ce4+ was close to 0.5 (Fig. 6
                        ). This indicated that Ce4+ and FDA exhibited a 1:1 ratio, which was consistent with the results obtained by the B–H curve. As shown in Fig. 6(b), according to Benesie-Hildebrand expression, the ratio [1/(F0 − F)] of FDA at 505 nm presented a linear relationship with the ratio of 1/[Ce4+]. The correlation coefficient was calculated as 0.998, suggesting that Ce4+ and FDA was coordinated by 1:1 stoichiometry. By metal ion combination, the electron was transferred from fluorescein unit to Ce4+ occurrence (LMCT) [28]. The mechanism is shown in Scheme 2
                        .

The mechanism of FDH and OCl− can also be demonstrated by the calculation of DFT. The HUMO of FDH localized on fluorescein fluorophore, while the LUMO delocalized on the 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine which conforms to the electronic cloud distribution of the PET process (Fig. 7
                        ). After FDH combined with OCl−, the energy level and electrical cloud distribution of probe become different. As shown in Fig. 7, the electron densities of HOMO were distributed over the xanthene part, while those of LUMO transferred to 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine and imine group. Based on above results, the final product and the corresponding mechanism are shown in Scheme 3
                        , were proposed.

Ce4+ or OCl− were added to the tap water, lake water and pool water obtained from Tianjin city and analyzed by FDA (Table 1
                        ) and FDH (Table 2
                        ). These results indicated that both FDA and FDH exhibited potential application in practical sample analysis.
